<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-179-426  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 179 426.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 10 1989 v6 n14 p38(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Phone users' rights are only part of the issue. (automaticnumbering identification) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shippen, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The privacy and legal rights issues surrounding automatic numberidentification (ANI) technology have been discussed, but theeconomics of the new service has not been considered.andP;  Telephonecompanies will have to purchase more announcement machines,upgrade current machines, and have the service available at everycentral office.andP;  All such costs would eventually be passed alongto the ratepayers, even those who do not subscribe to the service.andO;A new generation of phones with display units will also be spawnedby the new technology.andP;  And more services, such as declining toreceive unidentified calls, or declining to have a numberforwarded to a recipient, will also be brought to the market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsPrivacyRightsLegal IssuesEconomics of InformationCost of CommunicationsTelephone Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>